      Carbon risk transfer
   =20
 =20

Ahh   this is clever:

A veteran of alternative investment management has started pitching a new t=
ype of securitization he says would allow banks to cut the carbon footprint=
 of their balance sheets.
Andrew Hohns, a former managing director at hedge fund Mariner Investment G=
roup who now runs Newmarket Capital, says he=E2=80=99s currently in talks w=
ith a number of banks to construct such novel transfers.
For banks, repackaging and transferring the credit risk from their loan boo=
ks to less-regulated private fund managers is nothing new. The appeal for i=
nvestors on the other side of such deals is they can get double-digit retur=
ns, while banks get capital relief, freeing them up to do more business.
Newmarket, a Philadelphia-based alternative asset manager that specializes =
in structured credit, is now pitching a similar mechanism for banks to repa=
ckage and transfer their so-called financed emissions, which represent the =
greenhouse gas pollution linked to their lending and investment activities.=
 Banks that channel a lot of capital into the fossil-fuel industry, for exa=
mple, would have big financed emissions.

That is from Bloomberg=E2=80=99s Natasha White this week. The idea in credi=
t risk transfer is:
=09A bank lends money to companies.=09If those companies don=E2=80=99t pay=
=C2=A0back the loans, the bank loses money.=09Bank regulators require the b=
ank to have capital as a cushion against that possible loss, with the actua=
l amount of capital being sort of a crude function of how likely the regula=
tors think the loss is.=09The bank can =E2=80=9Ctransfer the credit risk=E2=
=80=9D of the loans to a hedge fund, meaning that, if the companies don=E2=
=80=99t pay back the loans, the bank doesn=E2=80=99t lose money, but the he=
dge fund does.=09The simplest way to do this is to sell the loans to the he=
dge fund, but usually when people say =E2=80=9Ccredit risk transfer=E2=80=
=9D they mean a more complicated transaction in which the hedge fund promis=
es that, if the companies don=E2=80=99t pay back the loans, the hedge fund =
will, so the bank doesn=E2=80=99t lose money. And in exchange the bank pays=
 the hedge fund a premium for insuring this risk.
  [1]

=09If you do this right, the bank will not have to have as much capital, an=
d the savings from reduced capital will be worth more to the bank than the =
premium that it pays to the hedge fund for the credit risk transfer. That i=
s: The market (the hedge funds) effectively=C2=A0assigns a lower credit ris=
k to the loans than capital regulators do, so there is a trade available in=
 which the bank saves money, and the hedge funds make money, by moving that=
 risk out of the regulated banking system.

Fine. But now do emissions risk. In addition to capital rules, now banks ge=
t bad publicity and possibly=C2=A0regulatory consequences=C2=A0if they lend=
 too much money to fossil fuel projects. (Or, in the US, too little.) There=
 are global standards for the carbon impact of banks=E2=80=99 activities, w=
ith separate treatment for =E2=80=9Cfinanced emissions=E2=80=9D (carbon emi=
ssions associated with loans and investments that banks make and hold on th=
eir books), =E2=80=9Cfacilitated emissions=E2=80=9D (emissions associated w=
ith stock and bond underwriting and loan syndication =E2=80=94=C2=A0that is=
, money that banks help companies raise=C2=A0but that does not come from th=
e banks themselves) and =E2=80=9Cinsurance-associated emissions.=E2=80=9D N=
ewmarket=E2=80=99s idea seems to address only financed emissions, which is =
fine; transferring facilitated emissions seems harder but possibly more fun=
.
  [2]

How do you transfer financed emissions? Well, the simplest way is, still, t=
o sell the loans to the hedge fund: If some loan on a bank=E2=80=99s balanc=
e sheet is associated with 10 tons of emissions, and you move it off the ba=
lance sheet, then the 10 tons of financed emissions goes away.
  [3]
 This is not a particularly complicated business, but it is a good pitch. Y=
ou go to a bank and say =E2=80=9Clook, you have a bunch of loans to oil and=
 gas companies, and people yell at you about them. Just sell us the loans a=
t, you know, 98 cents on the dollar, and that gets rid of both the credit r=
isk=C2=A0and=C2=A0the people yelling at you about financing carbon emission=
s. And we get 2% for helping you out.=E2=80=9D And in fact the plan seems t=
o be that the credit risk and carbon risk will go together:
The idea is to =E2=80=9Ctransfer the credit risk, but at the same time tran=
sfer the so-called emissions risk to a third-party investor outside of the =
banking system, such as ourselves,=E2=80=9D Hohns said.
That probably doesn=E2=80=99t=C2=A0exactly mean=C2=A0=E2=80=9Cjust sell us =
the loans,=E2=80=9D but it=E2=80=99s pretty close.
The fun financial engineering would be to transfer the emissions accounting=
=C2=A0without=C2=A0the credit risk.=C2=A0What would that even mean? With cr=
edit risk transfers, it=E2=80=99s pretty straightforward: If a bank=C2=A0tr=
ansfers the credit risk of a loan to a hedge fund, that means that, if the =
borrower doesn=E2=80=99t pay back the loan, the hedge fund makes up the dif=
ference and the bank doesn=E2=80=99t lose any money. With emissions, though=
, there is no real=C2=A0risk: If a bank lends an oil company $100 to build =
a refinery, and it expects that refinery to emit 100 tons of carbon, then t=
hose 100 tons just count against the bank=E2=80=99s financed emissions. The=
re is no relevant uncertainty, so no arbitrage; the market does not assign =
a lower amount of emissions to the trade than the standards do. Still one c=
ould imagine a few approaches:
=09The purely metaphysical approach: The bank pays a hedge fund $2, and in =
exchange the hedge fund says =E2=80=9Cactually I financed those emissions.=
=E2=80=9D I don=E2=80=99t think that would work, but who knows. =E2=80=9CAp=
plying a risk-transfer model to carbon emissions remains experimental,=E2=
=80=9D writes White,=C2=A0=E2=80=9Cin large part because it=E2=80=99s hard =
to assign monetary values to such risk and because no rules exist to guide =
such a construction.=E2=80=9D=09Something with carbon offsets. White: =E2=
=80=9CRyan Dunfield, chief executive of SAF Group, a Canadian private credi=
t investor, says he=E2=80=99s also had talks with banks about taking on the=
ir emissions risk. =E2=80=A6=C2=A0Structures that SAF has discussed with ba=
nks include a so-called black carbon pool, Dunfield said. The idea is to cr=
eate a vehicle into which banks can =E2=80=98move all their emissions-inten=
sive financings,=E2=80=99=C2=A0he said. SAF would then seek to match those =
with carbon offsets, he added.=E2=80=9D That way, the bank is not=C2=A0lend=
ing money to fossil fuel companies; it is=C2=A0lending money to a black car=
bon pool, whose net emissions (including offsets) are zero. So no financed =
emissions.=09Just sell the loans, and then buy back the credit risk. Sell t=
he loans to the hedge fund, have them live on its balance sheet, get them o=
ff the bank=E2=80=99s balance sheet, and then have the bank write credit in=
surance against the loans. Or, even better, sell the loans to the hedge fun=
d, have them live on the hedge fund=E2=80=99s balance sheet, and then have=
=C2=A0a different hedge fund=C2=A0write credit insurance against the loans.

It is interesting to think about pricing in the third case. Assume that a b=
ank makes a $100 loan to a fossil fuel company and would have to pay $5 to =
transfer its credit risk. How much is the carbon risk worth? Does the bank =
sell the loan for $94, the hedge fund=C2=A0buys credit insurance for $5, an=
d effectively they pay $1 for the carbon transfer?=C2=A0How much does the h=
edge fund need to be paid to take on the emissions as a=C2=A0pure accountin=
g matter, if the hedge fund is a private company that doesn=E2=80=99t have =
to report its emissions to anyone? Like, with the right structure =E2=80=94=
=C2=A0one in which I took no credit or liquidity risk and put up no money
  [4]
=C2=A0=E2=80=94=C2=A0I would probably be willing to take all of JPMorgan Ch=
ase & Co.=E2=80=99s carbon emissions off their hands, and put them on my ba=
lance sheet, for, you know,=C2=A0one basis point of notional value? I feel =
like that would probably be a nice payday for me and cost me nothing except=
 some time and effort to review the documents, which I would enjoy.

