Last month, a New York state court found Donald Trump liable for a somewhat=
 odd form of fraud. Over the years, Trump borrowed a lot of money from bank=
s, and as part of these deals the banks wanted financial statements from hi=
m. Because he is Donald Trump, he delivered inflated vanity financial state=
ments to the banks, and because he is Donald Trump, the banks ignored those=
 financial statements. Everyone knew he was lying about his wealth, because=
 he has very publicly done that for decades, but the banks were able to und=
erwrite the loans without paying too much attention to his inflated estimat=
es of his own net worth, and in fact the loans at issue in this case were p=
aid back and the banks did fine.
  [5]

As a philosophical matter, I think there=E2=80=99s a good argument that lyi=
ng about something=C2=A0immaterial=C2=A0to your banks should not be treated=
 as fraud, and if the banks knew you were lying about your net worth then t=
hat lie is not quite fraud.
  [6]
=C2=A0As a practical matter, though, if you are=C2=A0filling out a loan app=
lication at a bank and lying about how much money you have, you should prob=
ably expect to get in trouble. A lot of people do not have a sense of humor=
 about these things and are not interested in the philosophical arguments.
Trump was ordered to pay $454 million to the New York attorney general,=C2=
=A0and he plans to appeal. But to appeal he needs to post a bond for the fu=
ll judgment with the court, and he can=E2=80=99t come up with the money:

Donald Trump said he reached out to the world=E2=80=99s biggest insurance c=
ompanies to seek help in arranging an appeal bond covering the $454 million=
 verdict against him in New York=E2=80=99s civil fraud suit, and none would=
 take his real estate as collateral. They all want cash and Trump says he d=
oesn=E2=80=99t have enough.
The real estate mogul and former president will be forced to hold a =E2=80=
=9Cfire sale=E2=80=9D of his properties to raise enough cash if the bond is=
n=E2=80=99t waived while he challenges the verdict, Trump said in a filing =
Monday with a New York appeals court. The appeal bond is due March 25 if th=
e requirement isn=E2=80=99t put on hold.

This, I should say, is somewhat weird. His whole argument is that his banks=
 were in fact thrilled to lend him money, and that whatever was wrong in hi=
s financial statements didn=E2=80=99t matter because the banks knew he was =
worth far more than they were lending him. Now, though, nobody will give hi=
m money. His lawyers complain
  [7]
:
Diligent efforts ... including =E2=80=9Ccountless hours negotiating with on=
e of the largest insurance companies in the world,=E2=80=9D have proven tha=
t =E2=80=9Cobtaining an appeal bond in the full amount=E2=80=9D of the Judg=
ment =E2=80=9Cis not possible under the circumstances presented.=E2=80=9D T=
he amount of the judgment, with interest, exceeds $464 million, and very fe=
w bonding companies will consider a bond of anything approaching that=C2=A0=
magnitude. The remaining handful will not =E2=80=9Caccept hard assets such =
as real estate as collateral,=E2=80=9D but =E2=80=9Cwill only accept cash o=
r cash equivalents (such as marketable securities).=E2=80=9D Moreover, sure=
ties would typically =E2=80=9Crequire collateral of approximately 120% of t=
he amount of the judgment,=E2=80=9D which =E2=80=9Cwould require Defendants=
 to hand over collateral in the form of cash or cash equivalents of approxi=
mately=E2=80=9D $557 million.=C2=A0In addition, sureties would likely charg=
e bond premiums of approximately 2 percent per year with two years in advan=
ce =E2=80=94 an upfront cost over $18 million.=C2=A0
Where will Donald Trump get $557 million worth of marketable securities by =
March 25? Oh=C2=A0man, do I have amazing news for him. The New York Times r=
eported last month:

Former President Donald J. Trump=E2=80=99s stake in Trump Media & Technolog=
y Group, his social media company, could be worth as much as $4 billion onc=
e a long-delayed merger closes.
The deal, with Digital World Acquisition Corporation =E2=80=94 a publicly t=
raded shell company =E2=80=94 could provide him with a potential financial =
lifeline at a time when he must come up with the cash to pay a $454 million=
 penalty after a New York judge=E2=80=99s ruling in a civil fraud case.
Digital World has scheduled a March 22 shareholder vote on the merger with =
Trump Media, whose flagship product, Truth Social, has become the social me=
dia platform of choice for Mr. Trump to attack his critics and political op=
ponents.

The shareholder vote is this Friday; the bond is due on Monday. Pretty tigh=
t! There are problems. For one thing, the shareholders have to vote to appr=
ove the deal. They=C2=A0obviously=C2=A0should do that: DWAC=E2=80=99s stock=
 closed yesterday at $35.575 per share in anticipation of the deal; if the =
deal fails, shareholders will get back roughly $10.87 per share.
  [8]
=C2=A0They want the deal. But in the past, DWAC has failed to get sharehold=
er approval for obviously good things because its heavily retail shareholde=
r base doesn=E2=80=99t vote that much. I would be surprised if that happene=
d on the merger vote, but it=E2=80=99s not impossible.
Then, the deal has to close right after the vote. At that point, Trump will=
 personally have=C2=A0shares worth about $2.8 billion.
  [9]

Also, Trump=E2=80=99s shares are subject to a lockup agreement, so he=E2=80=
=99s not allowed to =E2=80=9Clend, offer, pledge, hypothecate, encumber, do=
nate, assign, sell, contract to sell =E2=80=A6=C2=A0or otherwise transfer o=
r dispose of=E2=80=9D his shares for six months, which presumably covers us=
ing them as collateral for a loan (or appeals bond). But the agreement is b=
etween Trump and DWAC, and DWAC could just waive it. It is not=C2=A0best pr=
actices=C2=A0or anything, as a capital markets matter, to waive the lockup =
an hour after the merger, but I think it is=C2=A0possible. Ordinarily you d=
on=E2=80=99t do it because shareholders will be mad about additional shares=
 flooding the market, but (1) if he just=C2=A0pledges his shares to a bank,=
 they won=E2=80=99t flood the market, and (2)=C2=A0the shareholders are pre=
sumably Trump fans and will be happy to help him fund his legal bills. Prob=
ably the stock would go=C2=A0up=C2=A0if they gave him a limited waiver for =
this.
The other problem is, if you were a bank, would you lend money against thos=
e shares? Maybe? Bloomberg=E2=80=99s Bailey Lipschultz reported last month:

=E2=80=9CHe needs the money but he can=E2=80=99t sell too much at once with=
out risking tanking the stock,=E2=80=9D said Usha Rodrigues, a professor at=
 the University of Georgia School of Law. =E2=80=9COnce the lockup is expir=
ed, he could use the shares as collateral for loans in order to access cash=
 without selling the shares.=E2=80=9D
And it=E2=80=99s unlikely a bank would lend him a large sum of money agains=
t the locked-up shares, according to industry watchers like University of F=
lorida finance professor Jay Ritter.

I guess I=E2=80=99m a little more optimistic than that, though I see his po=
int. The shares are worth billions of dollars at present market value, but =
TMTG has never actually made money,
  [10]
=C2=A0and a bank that lends money against a locked-up meme stock is making =
a risky bet that the shares=C2=A0will still be valuable in six months. A lo=
t can happen in six months! Still, at current prices, that=E2=80=99s a lot =
of collateral. It=E2=80=99s not an insane bet. You=E2=80=99d want recourse.=
=C2=A0
Mostly though it seems fitting. Trump was fined $454 million because of his=
 habit of inflating his own estimates of his wealth, basing his estimates o=
n how he feels rather than objective measures like cash flows or comparable=
 transactions. But then DWAC came along and gave him the opportunity to, in=
 effect, turn his celebrity into a publicly traded security. Lipschultz:
=E2=80=9CThis is a meme stock, it=E2=80=99s not the type of thing where you=
 bust out P/E ratios =E2=80=94 you can throw that out the window,=E2=80=9D =
said Matthew Tuttle, the chief executive and chief investment officer at Tu=
ttle Capital Management. =E2=80=9CDWAC has now become the de facto way to b=
et on or against Trump,=E2=80=9D he added.
The old world (=E2=80=9Cjust making up your net worth based on your feeling=
s is fraud=E2=80=9D) is dying at the exact same time that the new one (=E2=
=80=9Cactually there=E2=80=99s a stock ticker for how Donald Trump feels an=
d it has a market cap of several billion dollars=E2=80=9D) is being born, a=
nd if he times it just right maybe he can use the new stock to pay the old =
fine.

