China Evergrande Group is a Chinese real estate developer whose business mo=
del involved (1) selling apartments for cash up front and (2) then eventual=
ly building them. There are many attractions to this business model. In par=
ticular, in the early days, you feel rich: You have all this cash, from the=
 apartments you sold, and you haven=E2=80=99t spent any of it to build the =
apartments.
There are, however, obvious problems, or at least temptations. What if you =
take all that cash and spend it on executive salaries, or buying more land =
to build more apartments, or advertising to attract new buyers? Then, when =
you eventually get around to building the apartments that you already sold,=
 you might find out that the cash is all gone and you can=E2=80=99t afford =
to build them. That would be bad! You would have to go out and borrow more =
money just to build the apartments you already sold. Or, of course, you cou=
ld sell even=C2=A0more=C2=A0apartments, to raise the cash to build the ones=
 that you previously sold, but that only kicks the can down the road: Where=
 will you get the money to pay to build the apartments you=E2=80=99re selli=
ng now, if you use their purchase price to build the apartments you sold pr=
eviously? The problem snowballs.
One way to resist this temptation is accounting. Most accounting standards =
won=E2=80=99t let you count the purchase price as income the day you get it=
: You only recognize revenue when you actually deliver the apartment, when =
you fulfill your end of the deal. That money isn=E2=80=99t=C2=A0yours=C2=A0=
when you sell the apartment and get the money; it only becomes yours when y=
ou deliver the apartment, and the accounting ought to reflect that. If the =
accounting reflects that, you don=E2=80=99t look at your giant pile of cash=
 and think =E2=80=9Cwe=E2=80=99re rich and profitable, let=E2=80=99s spend =
it=E2=80=9D; you think =E2=80=9Coh wow, we gotta get to work building these=
 apartments.=E2=80=9D
Anyway,=C2=A0Evergrande has collapsed catastrophically over the last few ye=
ars=C2=A0and was ordered to liquidate this year. There were many problems =
=E2=80=94=C2=A0it had borrowed a lot of money, it was highly levered to Chi=
nese property prices =E2=80=94=C2=A0but this was one of them. For years, Ev=
ergrande was booking apartment sales as revenue before it completed the apa=
rtments. Eventually it ran into trouble, and, in an effort to get out of tr=
ouble, it cleaned up its accounting. From its (much delayed)=C2=A02021 annu=
al report:
Prior to 2021, the Group considered that the revenue is recognised when the=
 earlier of the acceptance of the property by the customer or according to =
the sales contract, the property was deemed to have been accepted by the cu=
stomer. However, since 2021, due to the Group gradually facing liquidity di=
fficulties, the Group believes that including the requirement for obtaining=
 construction completion certificates or delivery of property inventory to =
property owners for use as an additional condition for revenue recognition =
would better reflect the Group=E2=80=99s situation and have practical opera=
bility.
Before 2021, that is, Evergrande booked revenue when the apartment was =E2=
=80=9Cdeemed to have been accepted,=E2=80=9D a purely metaphysical concept =
that did not involve actually building the apartment. To the naked eye, thi=
s looks like booking the revenue before it was earned, and it led to tempta=
tion. From 2021 on, Evergrande=C2=A0apparently did the accounting right, bu=
t it didn=E2=80=99t even bother to correct its previous financial statement=
s: =E2=80=9Cafter the company experienced liquidity problems,=E2=80=9D it s=
aid, =E2=80=9Ca large number of financial and engineering staff left and th=
e Group was unable to identify or estimate the effect of implementing the c=
hange in revenue recognition treatment on historical financial statements.=
=E2=80=9D Whoops.=C2=A0GMT Research=C2=A0wrote last year
  [11]
:
At some point, it appears Evergrande=E2=80=99s primary purpose became raisi=
ng finance to fund its inflating balance sheet and keep the party going. Wh=
ile, correctly measured, the property business may not have been profitable=
, Evergrande=E2=80=99s ability to find new sources of financing was excepti=
onal, including wealth management products, insurance funds, new business v=
entures (bottled water, healthcare, electric vehicles etc.) and RMB130bn fr=
om strategic investors with the promise of an onshore listing.
An unprofitable business combined with an exceptional ability to raise mone=
y is in many ways the worst possible business, at least for the people givi=
ng you the money. Getting the accounting right is an important safeguard ag=
ainst that, but getting the accounting wrong=C2=A0does help with the financ=
ing. And so Bloomberg News reports:

China Evergrande Group=E2=80=99s alleged $78 billion revenue overstatement =
escalates the legal peril of founder Hui Ka Yan, who now stands at the cent=
er of one of the biggest financial fraud cases in history.
The nation=E2=80=99s top securities regulator said the developer=E2=80=99s =
onshore unit inflated revenue by recognizing sales in advance in the two ye=
ars through 2020 that led up to its default. It imposed a 4.18 billion yuan=
 ($581 million) fine against the unit.
Evergrande=E2=80=99s alleged fraud dwarfs that of Luckin Coffee Inc. and En=
ron Corp., dealing a blow to the reputation of its former auditor Pricewate=
rhouseCoopers LLP and the country=E2=80=99s financial oversight. It fuels c=
oncern about how widespread such accounting issues are, just as the new Chi=
na Securities Regulatory Commission chairman is trying to tighten oversight=
. =E2=80=A6
Regulators allege Hui instructed other personnel to =E2=80=9Cfalsely inflat=
e=E2=80=9D annual results. The onshore unit Hengda Real Estate Group booste=
d its 2019 revenue by about 214 billion yuan, and another 350 billion yuan =
in 2020, the regulator said. The inflated figures accounted for half of Hen=
gda=E2=80=99s total revenue in 2019, and 79% in 2020.
As the supervisor in charge, Hui used particularly =E2=80=9Cegregious=E2=80=
=9D means, the regulator said. Hengda also used these inflated figures in m=
arketing to issue a combined 20.8 billion yuan in bonds, the regulator said=
.

Obviously this is the sort of thing that a regulator will find interesting =
after Evergrande collapsed, though it is embarrassing for the regulator =E2=
=80=94=C2=A0and the auditors! =E2=80=94=C2=A0that they didn=E2=80=99t notic=
e it=C2=A0before. But when Evergrande was pulling in all that cash, I guess=
 everyone faced some temptations.

