      Don=E2=80=99t call bribes candies
   =20
 =20

One possibility is that bribing government officials is just routine in the=
 world of global commodity trading. Here is a Bloomberg News story about a =
former Vitol Group trader named Javier Aguilar, who was convicted last mont=
h=C2=A0of bribing Ecuadorian officials, and it seems like=C2=A0it would hav=
e been bigger news if he had=C2=A0not=C2=A0bribed them:

The revelations of the trial stretched far beyond Javier Aguilar and Vitol,=
 as witness after witness described a frenzied period of corruption in Ecua=
dor that extended across the oil trading industry. On the very first day, a=
 former Ecuadorian official stated flatly that he had been bribed not just =
by Vitol, but also by Trafigura Group and Gunvor Group =E2=80=94 together, =
three of the four largest independent oil traders. (The other member of the=
 quartet, Glencore Plc, has not been accused of wrongdoing in Ecuador but i=
n 2022 pleaded guilty to separate charges of corruption in eight other coun=
tries.) =E2=80=A6
At one point Antonio Per=C3=A9 was asked if he had ever helped a client wit=
h government business without paying a bribe to a government official. =E2=
=80=9CI=E2=80=99m not sure,=E2=80=9D he replied. =E2=80=9CI cannot recall o=
ne.=E2=80=9D

If you bribe one public official once in your life, I suppose you might be,=
 like, giddy and awkward about it. But if you bribe every official on every=
 deal, I would expect that you=E2=80=99d get pretty businesslike about it.=
=C2=A0If every deal involves a bribe, there will be professional networks o=
f bribe consultants who will do the work in a professional manner, and in f=
act there are:

By adding more intermediary layers between corrupt traders and corrupt gove=
rnment officials, the industry has fueled a thriving underbelly of =E2=80=
=9Cconsultants=E2=80=9D and =E2=80=9Cbrokers=E2=80=9D with bank accounts in=
 opaque offshore jurisdictions.
=E2=80=9CIn our country, in that area, it was common knowledge that in orde=
r to do business with the government, most of the time you had to pay bribe=
s,=E2=80=9D Antonio Per=C3=A9 said.

Per=C3=A9 is a former Ecuadorian government employee who left to become a b=
ribe consultant:
By the time he met Aguilar, Per=C3=A9 and his brother Enrique had set thems=
elves up as a one-stop shop for oil traders looking to do business in Ecuad=
or. In practice, they were a clearinghouse for bribes to Ecuadorian governm=
ent officials.
Which is a good business:
But it was the Per=C3=A9s who made the fattest margins. Of the roughly $100=
 million they admitted receiving from oil traders seeking business in Ecuad=
or, the brothers kept about half for themselves.
One advantage to all this professionalism, if you are paying or receiving b=
ribes, is that it can create some deniability. If on every deal you and all=
 of your competitors pay consulting fees to a handful of consultants who wo=
rk out of normal office buildings and have business cards that say =E2=80=
=9Cenergy consultant,=E2=80=9D then if the authorities ask questions you ca=
n say =E2=80=9Cah yes we had to pay that consultant for consulting,=E2=80=
=9D and it will be a little hard for them to prove that you did anything il=
legal. Perhaps at some point somebody hands a government official a sack of=
 cash in a parking lot, but having=C2=A0many=C2=A0parts of the business loo=
k open and traceable and normal can give it all a veneer of legitimacy. The=
 article features a spreadsheet of bribes. Businesslike!
On the other hand, years of writing about bribery has taught me that absolu=
tely no one can resist the allure of talking in dumb code that makes them l=
ook more guilty:

Sometimes their pseudo-spycraft veered towards the absurd: they referred to=
 Switzerland as the =E2=80=9Ccountry of cheese.=E2=80=9D Rather than naming=
 Vitol=E2=80=99s competitors Trafigura and Glencore, they talked of =E2=80=
=9Cthe T and the G.=E2=80=9D ...
It was not just Ecuadorian officials that Vitol bribed via Hanst. He sent m=
oney to another middleman who handed it over, sometimes in a Houston parkin=
g lot, to employees of Mexico=E2=80=99s state oil company Pemex, who messag=
ed each other excitedly about deliveries of =E2=80=9Ccandies.=E2=80=9D=C2=
=A0

Nobody=E2=80=99s going to read those messages and think you meant candies!

