<table class=3D"header" width=3D"100%" border=3D"0" cellspacing=3D"0" cellp=
adding=3D"0">
<tr>
<td class=3D"body-header-container" style=3D"border-collapse: collapse; mso=
-table-lspace: 0pt; mso-table-rspace: 0pt;">
<h2 style=3D"font-weight: bold; font-family: &quot;Arial Black&quot;, Arial=
, Helvetica, sans-serif; letter-spacing: -1px; font-size: 20px; border-bott=
om-width: 1px; border-bottom-style: dotted; margin: 0px; padding: 16px 0px =
5px;">Carbon risk transfer</h2>
</td>
</tr>
</table>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Ahh <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusi=
ness.com/click/34741977.257361/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9uZXdzL2Fy=
dGljbGVzLzIwMjQtMDMtMTcvaGVkZ2UtZnVuZC12ZXRlcmFuLXBpdGNoZXMtZmlyc3QtZXZlci1=
lbWlzc2lvbnMtcmlzay10cmFuc2ZlcnM_Y21waWQ9QkJEMDMxOTI0X01PTkVZU1RVRkYmdXRtX2=
1lZGl1bT1lbWFpbCZ1dG1fc291cmNlPW5ld3NsZXR0ZXImdXRtX3Rlcm09MjQwMzE5JnV0bV9jY=
W1wYWlnbj1tb25leXN0dWZm/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBe5ebe309" itemprop=3D"Stor=
yLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; t=
ext-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-co=
lor: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">  this i=
s clever</a>:</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">A veteran of alternative investment management=
 has started pitching a new type of securitization he says would allow bank=
s to cut the carbon footprint of their balance sheets.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Andrew Hohns, a former managing director at he=
dge fund Mariner Investment Group who now runs Newmarket Capital, says he=
=E2=80=99s currently in talks with a number of banks to construct such nove=
l transfers.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">For banks, repackaging and transferring the cr=
edit risk from their loan books to less-regulated private fund managers is =
nothing new. The appeal for investors on the other side of such deals is th=
ey can get double-digit returns, while banks get capital relief, freeing th=
em up to do more business.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Newmarket, a Philadelphia-based alternative as=
set manager that specializes in structured credit, is now pitching a simila=
r mechanism for banks to repackage and transfer their so-called financed em=
issions, which represent the greenhouse gas pollution linked to their lendi=
ng and investment activities. Banks that channel a lot of capital into the =
fossil-fuel industry, for example, would have big financed emissions.</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">That is from Bloomberg=E2=80=99s Natasha White=
 this week. The idea in credit risk transfer is:</p>
<ol style=3D"list-style-type: decimal; padding-left: 40px; margin: 16px 0;"=
>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">A bank lends money to companies.</li>=
=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">If those companies don=E2=80=99t pay=
=C2=A0back the loans, the bank loses money.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bott=
om: 5px;">Bank regulators require the bank to have capital as a cushion aga=
inst that possible loss, with the actual amount of capital being sort of a =
crude function of how likely the regulators think the loss is.</li>=09<li s=
tyle=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">The bank can =E2=80=9Ctransfer the credit risk=
=E2=80=9D of the loans to a hedge fund, meaning that, if the companies don=
=E2=80=99t pay back the loans, the bank doesn=E2=80=99t lose money, but the=
 hedge fund does.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">The simplest way=
 to do this is to sell the loans to the hedge fund, but usually when people=
 say =E2=80=9Ccredit risk transfer=E2=80=9D they mean a <a href=3D"https://=
link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/34741977.257361/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cud3NqL=
mNvbS9maW5hbmNlL2JhbmtpbmcvYmFuay1zeW50aGV0aWMtcmlzay10cmFuc2ZlcnMtYmFzZWwt=
ZW5kZ2FtZS02MjQxMGY2Yw/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB90caf6aa" itemprop=3D"Story=
Link" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; te=
xt-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-col=
or: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">more comp=
licated transaction</a> in which the hedge fund promises that, if the compa=
nies don=E2=80=99t pay back the loans, the hedge fund will, so the bank doe=
sn=E2=80=99t lose money. And in exchange the bank pays the hedge fund a pre=
mium for insuring this risk.<a class=3D"footnote-index" href=3D"#footnote-1=
" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-=
width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: none !import=
ant; background-color: transparent !important; display: inline-block;">
<span>[1]</span>
</a>
</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">If you do this right, the bank wi=
ll not have to have as much capital, and the savings from reduced capital w=
ill be worth more to the bank than the premium that it pays to the hedge fu=
nd for the credit risk transfer. That is: The market (the hedge funds) effe=
ctively=C2=A0<em>assigns a lower credit risk </em>to the loans than capital=
 regulators do, so there is a trade available in which the bank saves money=
, and the hedge funds make money, by moving that risk out of the regulated =
banking system.</li>
</ol>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Fine. But now do emissions risk. In addition t=
o capital rules, now banks get bad publicity and possibly=C2=A0<a href=3D"h=
ttps://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/34741977.257361/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3=
cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9uZXdzL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjMtMTAtMTIvZXVyb3BlLWFkZHMtZXNnL=
XRvLWJhbmstY2FwaXRhbC1ydWxlcy1tYXJraW5nLWEtd29ybGQtZmlyc3Q_Y21waWQ9QkJEMDMx=
OTI0X01PTkVZU1RVRkYmdXRtX21lZGl1bT1lbWFpbCZ1dG1fc291cmNlPW5ld3NsZXR0ZXImdXR=
tX3Rlcm09MjQwMzE5JnV0bV9jYW1wYWlnbj1tb25leXN0dWZm/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB=
e800f2a6" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" =
style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-wi=
dth: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; backgro=
und-color: #ccc;">regulatory consequences</a>=C2=A0if they lend too much mo=
ney to fossil fuel projects. (Or, in the US, <a href=3D"https://link.mail.b=
loombergbusiness.com/click/34741977.257361/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cudGV4YXN0cmlidW5l=
Lm9yZy8yMDIyLzA4LzI0L3RleGFzLWJveWNvdHQtY29tcGFuaWVzLWZvc3NpbC1mdWVscy8/607=
f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB12c1bc5c" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemsco=
pe" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !impor=
tant; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom=
-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">too little</a>.) There are <a href=
=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/34741977.257361/aHR0cHM6L=
y9jYXJib25hY2NvdW50aW5nZmluYW5jaWFscy5jb20vZW4vc3RhbmRhcmQ/607f07ceef4b8524=
a319a23cB37d227a7" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D=
"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-=
bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid=
; background-color: #ccc;">global standards</a> for the carbon impact of ba=
nks=E2=80=99 activities, with separate treatment for =E2=80=9Cfinanced emis=
sions=E2=80=9D (carbon emissions associated with loans and investments that=
 banks make and hold on their books), =E2=80=9Cfacilitated emissions=E2=80=
=9D (emissions associated with stock and bond underwriting and loan syndica=
tion =E2=80=94=C2=A0that is, money that banks help companies raise=C2=A0but=
 that does not come from the banks themselves) and =E2=80=9Cinsurance-assoc=
iated emissions.=E2=80=9D Newmarket=E2=80=99s idea seems to address only fi=
nanced emissions, which is fine; transferring facilitated emissions seems h=
arder but possibly more fun.<a class=3D"footnote-index" href=3D"#footnote-2=
" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-=
width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: none !import=
ant; background-color: transparent !important; display: inline-block;">
<span>[2]</span>
</a></p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">How do you transfer financed emissions? Well, =
the simplest way is, still, to sell the loans to the hedge fund: If some lo=
an on a bank=E2=80=99s balance sheet is associated with 10 tons of emission=
s, and you move it off the balance sheet, then the 10 tons of financed emis=
sions goes away.<a class=3D"footnote-index" href=3D"#footnote-3" style=3D"c=
olor: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; =
border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: none !important; backgro=
und-color: transparent !important; display: inline-block;">
<span>[3]</span>
</a> This is not a particularly complicated business, but it is a good pitc=
h. You go to a bank and say =E2=80=9Clook, you have a bunch of loans to oil=
 and gas companies, and people yell at you about them. Just sell us the loa=
ns at, you know, 98 cents on the dollar, and that gets rid of both the cred=
it risk=C2=A0<em>and=C2=A0</em>the people yelling at you about financing ca=
rbon emissions. And we get 2% for helping you out.=E2=80=9D And in fact the=
 plan seems to be that the credit risk and carbon risk will go together:</p=
>
<blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The idea is to =E2=80=9Ctransfer t=
he credit risk, but at the same time transfer the so-called emissions risk =
to a third-party investor outside of the banking system, such as ourselves,=
=E2=80=9D Hohns said.</p></blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">That probably doesn=E2=80=99t=C2=A0<em>exactly=
 mean=C2=A0</em>=E2=80=9Cjust sell us the loans,=E2=80=9D but it=E2=80=99s =
pretty close.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The fun financial engineering would be to tran=
sfer the emissions accounting=C2=A0<em>without=C2=A0</em>the credit risk.=
=C2=A0What would that even mean? With credit risk transfers, it=E2=80=99s p=
retty straightforward: If a bank=C2=A0transfers the credit risk of a loan t=
o a hedge fund, that means that, if the borrower doesn=E2=80=99t pay back t=
he loan, the hedge fund makes up the difference and the bank doesn=E2=80=99=
t lose any money. With emissions, though, there is no real=C2=A0<em>risk</e=
m>: If a bank lends an oil company $100 to build a refinery, and it expects=
 that refinery to emit 100 tons of carbon, then those 100 tons just count a=
gainst the bank=E2=80=99s financed emissions. There is no relevant uncertai=
nty, so no arbitrage; the market does not assign a lower amount of emission=
s to the trade than the standards do. Still one could imagine a few approac=
hes:</p>
<ol style=3D"list-style-type: decimal; padding-left: 40px; margin: 16px 0;"=
>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">The purely metaphysical approach: The=
 bank pays a hedge fund $2, and in exchange the hedge fund says =E2=80=9Cac=
tually I financed those emissions.=E2=80=9D I don=E2=80=99t think that woul=
d work, but who knows. =E2=80=9CApplying a risk-transfer model to carbon em=
issions remains experimental,=E2=80=9D writes White,=C2=A0=E2=80=9Cin large=
 part because it=E2=80=99s hard to assign monetary values to such risk and =
because no rules exist to guide such a construction.=E2=80=9D</li>=09<li st=
yle=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Something with carbon offsets. White: =E2=80=9C=
Ryan Dunfield, chief executive of SAF Group, a Canadian private credit inve=
stor, says he=E2=80=99s also had talks with banks about taking on their emi=
ssions risk. =E2=80=A6=C2=A0Structures that SAF has discussed with banks in=
clude a so-called black carbon pool, Dunfield said. The idea is to create a=
 vehicle into which banks can =E2=80=98move all their emissions-intensive f=
inancings,=E2=80=99=C2=A0he said. SAF would then seek to match those with c=
arbon offsets, he added.=E2=80=9D That way, the bank is not=C2=A0<em>lendin=
g money to fossil fuel companies</em>; it is=C2=A0<em>lending money to a bl=
ack carbon pool</em>, whose net emissions (including offsets) are zero. So =
no financed emissions.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Just sell t=
he loans, and then buy back the credit risk. Sell the loans to the hedge fu=
nd, have them live on its balance sheet, get them off the bank=E2=80=99s ba=
lance sheet, and then have the bank write credit insurance against the loan=
s. Or, even better, sell the loans to the hedge fund, have them live on the=
 hedge fund=E2=80=99s balance sheet, and then have=C2=A0<em>a different hed=
ge fund=C2=A0</em>write credit insurance against the loans.</li>
</ol>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">It is interesting to think about pricing in th=
e third case. Assume that a bank makes a $100 loan to a fossil fuel company=
 and would have to pay $5 to transfer its credit risk. How much is the carb=
on risk worth? Does the bank sell the loan for $94, the hedge fund=C2=A0buy=
s credit insurance for $5, and effectively they pay $1 for the carbon trans=
fer?=C2=A0How much does the hedge fund need to be paid to take on the emiss=
ions as a=C2=A0<em>pure accounting matter</em>, if the hedge fund is a priv=
ate company that doesn=E2=80=99t have to report its emissions to anyone? Li=
ke, with the right structure =E2=80=94=C2=A0one in which I took no credit o=
r liquidity risk and put up no money<a class=3D"footnote-index" href=3D"#fo=
otnote-4" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border=
-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: none=
 !important; background-color: transparent !important; display: inline-bloc=
k;">
<span>[4]</span>
</a>=C2=A0=E2=80=94=C2=A0I would probably be willing to take all of JPMorga=
n Chase &amp; Co.=E2=80=99s carbon emissions off their hands, and put them =
on my balance sheet, for, you know,=C2=A0one basis point of notional value?=
 I feel like that would probably be a nice payday for me and cost me nothin=
g except some time and effort to review the documents, which I would enjoy.=
</p>
