mportant; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bo=
ttom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">standards</a> won=E2=80=99t let=
 you count the purchase price as income the day you get it: You only recogn=
ize revenue when you actually deliver the apartment, when you fulfill your =
end of the deal. That money isn=E2=80=99t=C2=A0<em>yours</em>=C2=A0when you=
 sell the apartment and get the money; it only becomes yours when you deliv=
er the apartment, and the accounting ought to reflect that. If the accounti=
ng reflects that, you don=E2=80=99t look at your giant pile of cash and thi=
nk =E2=80=9Cwe=E2=80=99re rich and profitable, let=E2=80=99s spend it=E2=80=
=9D; you think =E2=80=9Coh wow, we gotta get to work building these apartme=
nts.=E2=80=9D</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Anyway,=C2=A0Evergrande has collapsed catastro=
phically over the last few years=C2=A0and was <a href=3D"https://link.mail.=
bloombergbusiness.com/click/34741977.257361/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmN=
vbS9uZXdzL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjQtMDEtMzAvZXZlcmdyYW5kZS1saXF1aWRhdGlvbi10by1sZW=
F2ZS1saXR0bGUtZm9yLWNyZWRpdG9ycy10by1jbGFpbT9jbXBpZD1CQkQwMzE5MjRfTU9ORVlTV=
FVGRiZ1dG1fbWVkaXVtPWVtYWlsJnV0bV9zb3VyY2U9bmV3c2xldHRlciZ1dG1fdGVybT0yNDAz=
MTkmdXRtX2NhbXBhaWduPW1vbmV5c3R1ZmY/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBe7468942" item=
prop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color=
: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; bord=
er-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #cc=
c;">ordered to liquidate</a> this year. There were many problems =E2=80=94=
=C2=A0it had borrowed a lot of money, it was highly levered to Chinese prop=
erty prices =E2=80=94=C2=A0but this was one of them. For years, Evergrande =
was booking apartment sales as revenue before it completed the apartments. =
Eventually it ran into trouble, and, in an effort to get out of trouble, it=
 cleaned up its accounting. From its (much delayed)=C2=A0<a href=3D"https:/=
/link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/34741977.257361/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cxLmhr=
ZXhuZXdzLmhrL2xpc3RlZGNvL2xpc3Rjb25ld3Mvc2Voay8yMDIzLzA4MzAvMjAyMzA4MzAwMjM=
xNS5wZGY/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB28d74f98" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscop=
e=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration:=
 none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; b=
order-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">2021 annual report</a>:=
</p>
<blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Prior to 2021, the Group considere=
d that the revenue is recognised when the earlier of the acceptance of the =
property by the customer or according to the sales contract, the property w=
as deemed to have been accepted by the customer. However, since 2021, due t=
o the Group gradually facing liquidity difficulties, the Group believes tha=
t including the requirement for obtaining construction completion certifica=
tes or delivery of property inventory to property owners for use as an addi=
tional condition for revenue recognition would better reflect the Group=E2=
=80=99s situation and have practical operability.</p></blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Before 2021, that is, Evergrande booked revenu=
e when the apartment was =E2=80=9Cdeemed to have been accepted,=E2=80=9D a =
purely metaphysical concept that did not involve actually building the apar=
tment. To the naked eye, this looks like booking the revenue before it was =
earned, and it led to temptation. From 2021 on, Evergrande=C2=A0apparently =
did the accounting right, but it didn=E2=80=99t even bother to correct its =
previous financial statements: =E2=80=9Cafter the company experienced liqui=
dity problems,=E2=80=9D it said, =E2=80=9Ca large number of financial and e=
ngineering staff left and the Group was unable to identify or estimate the =
effect of implementing the change in revenue recognition treatment on histo=
rical financial statements.=E2=80=9D Whoops.=C2=A0<a href=3D"https://link.m=
ail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/34741977.257361/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuZ210cmVzZWF=
yY2guY29tL2VuL3Jlc2VhcmNoL25ld3NsZXR0ZXItZXZlcmdyYW5kZS1uZXZlci1wcm9maXRhYm=
xlLw/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB037b9020" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D=
"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: non=
e !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; borde=
r-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">GMT Research</a>=C2=A0wrote=
 last year<a class=3D"footnote-index" href=3D"#footnote-11" style=3D"color:=
 #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; borde=
r-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: none !important; background-c=
olor: transparent !important; display: inline-block;">
<span>[11]</span>
</a>:</p>
<blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">At some point, it appears Evergran=
de=E2=80=99s primary purpose became raising finance to fund its inflating b=
alance sheet and keep the party going. While, correctly measured, the prope=
rty business may not have been profitable, Evergrande=E2=80=99s ability to =
find new sources of financing was exceptional, including wealth management =
products, insurance funds, new business ventures (bottled water, healthcare=
, electric vehicles etc.) and RMB130bn from strategic investors with the pr=
omise of an onshore listing.</p></blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">An unprofitable business combined with an exce=
ptional ability to raise money is in many ways the worst possible business,=
 at least for the people giving you the money. Getting the accounting right=
 is an important safeguard against that, but getting the accounting <em>wro=
ng=C2=A0</em>does help with the financing. And so <a href=3D"https://link.m=
ail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/34741977.257361/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJ=
nLmNvbS9uZXdzL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjQtMDMtMTkvY2hpbmEtYWNjdXNlcy1ldmVyZ3JhbmRlLW=
9mLTc4LWJpbGxpb24tZnJhdWQtYW1vbmctd29yc3QtZXZlcj9jbXBpZD1CQkQwMzE5MjRfTU9OR=
VlTVFVGRiZ1dG1fbWVkaXVtPWVtYWlsJnV0bV9zb3VyY2U9bmV3c2xldHRlciZ1dG1fdGVybT0y=
NDAzMTkmdXRtX2NhbXBhaWduPW1vbmV5c3R1ZmY/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB59c63dfc" =
itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"c=
olor: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; =
border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color:=
 #ccc;">Bloomberg News reports</a>:</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">China Evergrande Group=E2=80=99s alleged $78 b=
illion revenue overstatement escalates the legal peril of founder Hui Ka Ya=
n, who now stands at the center of one of the biggest financial fraud cases=
 in history.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The nation=E2=80=99s top securities regulator =
said the developer=E2=80=99s onshore unit inflated revenue by recognizing s=
ales in advance in the two years through 2020 that led up to its default. I=
t imposed a 4.18 billion yuan ($581 million) fine against the unit.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Evergrande=E2=80=99s alleged fraud dwarfs that=
 of Luckin Coffee Inc. and Enron Corp., dealing a blow to the reputation of=
 its former auditor PricewaterhouseCoopers LLP and the country=E2=80=99s fi=
nancial oversight. It fuels concern about how widespread such accounting is=
sues are, just as the new China Securities Regulatory Commission chairman i=
s trying to tighten oversight. =E2=80=A6</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Regulators allege Hui instructed other personn=
el to =E2=80=9Cfalsely inflate=E2=80=9D annual results. The onshore unit He=
ngda Real Estate Group boosted its 2019 revenue by about 214 billion yuan, =
and another 350 billion yuan in 2020, the regulator said. The inflated figu=
res accounted for half of Hengda=E2=80=99s total revenue in 2019, and 79% i=
n 2020.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">As the supervisor in charge, Hui used particul=
arly =E2=80=9Cegregious=E2=80=9D means, the regulator said. Hengda also use=
d these inflated figures in marketing to issue a combined 20.8 billion yuan=
 in bonds, the regulator said.</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Obviously this is the sort of thing that a reg=
ulator will find interesting after Evergrande collapsed, though it is embar=
rassing for the regulator =E2=80=94=C2=A0and the auditors! =E2=80=94=C2=A0t=
hat they didn=E2=80=99t notice it=C2=A0<em>before</em>. But when Evergrande=
 was pulling in all that cash, I guess everyone faced some temptations.</p>
